# 4. a. Significant Difference between charges of people who smoke and those who don't.
#       For this, we'll do a t-test.
#
#       The Null Hypothesis(H0) here, would be that there is no significant difference between the two populations => H0 => μ1 = μ2.
#
#       The Alternate Hypothesis(H1) would be that there is a significant difference => H1 => μ1 != μ2.
#
#       H0 => Means of Charges for smokers and non-smokers are same.
#       H1 => Means of Charges for smokers and non-smokers are different.
#
#       Taking the two groups:

smokers = df[df["smoker"] == "yes"]
non_smokers = df[df["smoker"] == "no"]

#       Calculating the t-value and p-value with t-test

t_smoking, p_smoking = stats.ttest_ind(smokers['charges'], non_smokers['charges'])
print("t = " + str(t_smoking))
print("p = " + str(p_smoking))

t = 46.664921172723716
p = 8.271435842177219e-283
In [75]:
# 4. b. Since, p < 0.05 and t is significantly high => Reject the Null Hypothesis at 5% significance level 
#              => Alternate Hypothesis stands
#       H1 => Charges for smokers and non-smokers are different.

# 4. b. Significant Difference between bmis of males and females.
#       For this, we'll do a t-test.
#
#       The Null Hypothesis(H0) here, would be that there is no significant difference between the two populations => H0 => μ1 = μ2.
#
#       The Alternate Hypothesis(H1) would be that there is a significant difference => H1 => μ1 != μ2.
#
#       H0 => Means of Bmi for males and females are same.
#       H1 => Means of Bmi for males and females are different.
#
#       Taking the two groups:

males = df[df["sex"] == "male"]
females = df[df["sex"] == "female"]

#       Calculating the t-value and p-value with t-test

t_genderbmi, p_genderbmi = stats.ttest_ind(males['bmi'], females['bmi'])
print("t = " + str(t_genderbmi))
print("p = " + str(p_genderbmi))

t = 1.696752635752224
p = 0.08997637178984932

# 4. c. Significant Difference between Smokers in different Genders
#       For this, we'll do a z-test of proportions.
#
#       The Null Hypothesis(H0) here, would be that there is no significant difference between smokers in two genders.
#
#       The Alternate Hypothesis(H1) would be that there is a significant difference between smokers in two genders.
#
#       H0 => Proportion of Smokers in males and females are same.
#       H1 => Proportion of Smokers in males and females are different.
#
#       From previous computations, we have

female_smokers = smokers.sex.value_counts()[1]
male_smokers = smokers.sex.value_counts()[0]

total_females = females.sex.value_counts()[0]
total_males = males.sex.value_counts()[0]

print(f' The proportions of smokers in females and males = {round(115/662, 2)} and {round(159/676, 2)} respectively.')

 The proportions of smokers in females and males = 0.17 and 0.24 respectively.
In [79]:
# 4. c. 
#      Now, the propertions are different but, lets check for significant difference.

z_genderSmokers, p_genderSmokers = proportions_ztest([female_smokers, male_smokers], [total_females, total_males])

if p_genderSmokers < 0.05:
    print(f' With p-value {round(p_genderSmokers, 4)}, the difference is significant i.e. we reject the Null Hypothesis')
else:
    print(f' With p-value {round(p_genderSmokers, 4)}, there is no significant difference i.e. we accept the Null Hypothesis')

 With p-value 0.0053, the difference is significant i.e. we reject the Null Hypothesis

# 4. d. Difference of bmi between women with no children, one child and two children.
#       For this, we'll do an ANOVA test.
#
#       The Null Hypothesis(H0) here, would be that there is no significant difference => H0 => μ1 = μ2 = μ3.
#
#       The Alternate Hypothesis(H1) would be that there is a significant difference => H1 => Any one μ differs.
#
#       H0 => Means of Bmi for women with no children, one child and two children are same.
#       H1 => Means of Bmi for women with no children, one child and two children are different.

#       Getting the 3 groups:

no_children_group = females[females['children'] == 0]
one_child_group = females[females['children'] == 1]
two_children_group = females[females['children'] == 2]

#       Forming a separate dataFrame:

women_children_df = pd.DataFrame()

df1 = pd.DataFrame({'Group_Type':'No_Children_Females', 'BMI': no_children_group['bmi']})
df2 = pd.DataFrame({'Group_Type':'One_Child_Females', 'BMI': one_child_group['bmi']})
df3 = pd.DataFrame({'Group_Type':'Two_Children_Females', 'BMI': two_children_group['bmi']})

women_children_df = women_children_df.append(df1)
women_children_df = women_children_df.append(df2)
women_children_df = women_children_df.append(df3)

# 4. d.
#      From the Box Plot, it seems the bmi of the three groups are quite similarly distributed.

#      For Significant difference, lets calculate the ANOVA table.
